			<p><b>Adiaphoron</b> (plural: <b>adiaphora</b> from the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greek_language" title="Greek language">Greek</a> ἀδιάφορα "indifferent things") was a concept used in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stoic" title="Stoic" class="mw-redirect">Stoic</a> philosophy to indicate things which were outside of moral law – that is, actions which are neither morally mandated nor morally forbidden.</p>
<p><i>Adiaphora</i> in Christianity refer to matters not regarded as essential to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faith" title="Faith">faith</a>, but nevertheless as permissible for Christians or allowed in church. What is specifically considered adiaphora depends on the specific theology in view.</p>
